results.notes:
This mushroom was growing from the side of a dead Black Willow (Salix nigra) a few feet from a small creek that runs through the park. I collected the specimen and took it home to attempt identification.

I am just a beginner, so arriving at this possible identification was difficult for me. At first, I posted a description and the photos to a Texas Facebook page for help with the identification (no comments from the group). A few days later, someone else posted a photo of a mushroom that looked similar to mine and had used the name Trametes lactinea. Since the new posting looked similar to my specimen, I had a clue to the genus (maybe).

This clue started a chain of research that seemed to suggest that the taxonomy within the genus Trametes was not settled. I read some papers that mentioned that a new genus Leiotrametes was being used as of 2012 and that lactinea was now considered part of that genus. Still I could not decide if mine was T. cubensis or L. lactinea. I contacted a person that I found on iNaturalist who seems to be an expert in the field, and he was of the opinion that T. cubensis and L. lactinea were synonomous. Other source suggested that T. cubensis was distinct, but does not occur in the US.

I could be way off here, but this is the best I can do with my limited experience.

12/29/2019 After additional reading, I want to call this Trametes lactinea.

DATE: 02 OCT 2019

FORAY ID: SSMC MF Project.

SITE NAME: Southeast of Copper Creek Bridge, just off FS Road 37, near Mt Rainier Park.

iNat #: 34422428

NEARBY FLORA: Conifer: Douglas Fir, Hemlock; Deciduous: Vine Maple, Red Huckleberry. Vanilla Leaf; Evergreen: Oregon Grape, Sword Fern.

SUBSTRATE: At the base of a Douglas Fir (secondary growth), Leaf Litter, Dense Humus Soil, Needle Duff, Moss.

HABIT: Few (4 within 1-foot area).

LIGHT EXPOSURE: Shade to partial shade.

ODOR: Indistinct.

TASTE: Unknown.

REFERENCES: Mushrooms of the Redwood Coast (Siegel & Schwarz), pg 168;
Mushrooms of the Pacific Northwest (Trudell & Ammirati), pg 152.

DETAILED PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION:

CAP: All specimens taken and observed were newly emerging: 2.5 3 cm across. Convex, An Olive-Green and Brown, almost camouflage-like coloring. Margin is Inrolled, distinct, regular, with sharp edges. Outer skin is very-thin.

GILLS: Pale Cream colored. Narrowly attached, with a slight Notch, and close. .

STIPE: ~ 3.5 cm long, Central Attachment with a Large Marginate, slightly Depressed Base. Base is Viscid and has a Yellowish-Brown Color; larger across than the Cap (~ 3.5 4 cm).

PARTIAL VEIL: Substantial Cortina which is nearly clear and a Glassy-like Reflectiveness.. With growth, the Cortina becomes a Pale-Yellow, Rusty-brown sheen which breaks up, but is retained slightly on the Cap Margin and just below the Stipe Apex.

FLESH: Predominantly Bone White, with some slight mottled discoloring…a pale-to-medium brown.

SPORES: Ostensibly Rusty Brown.

MYCELIA: White, Dense, and extending deeply into the Substrate…~ 15 cm.

NOTE: DNA sequence shows the specimen has over 600 base pairs and is a 100% match to C.subsulfurinus.

Trees present in the general area were Fagus grandifolia, Quercus sect, Lobatae, Quercus alba, Carya spp., Pinus echinata, Pinus rigida, Carpinus caroliniana, Ostrya virginiana, Tilia americana, Sassafras albidum, Oxydendron arboreum, Kalmia latifolia, Liriodendron tulipiferum, Acer saccharum and other hardwoods. Paraphyses cylindrical. Asci unitunicate, operculate, thin-walled, with amyloid apices and 8 uniseriate spores. Spores hyaline with blunt ridges forming reticula and with 2 guttules.
